      <p>When it comes time to close on your home, you have options. Gone are the days when everyone had to squeeze into a conference room at a title company's office. Today, many title companies — including <a href="/">OnRecord Title</a> — offer mobile closing services that bring the entire closing experience to your doorstep.</p>

      <p>But which option is right for you? In this guide, we'll break down the differences between mobile and office closings so you can make an informed choice.</p>

      <h2>What Is a Mobile Closing?</h2>

      <p>A mobile closing is exactly what it sounds like: instead of traveling to the title company's office, a <strong>closing agent comes directly to you</strong>. They bring all the necessary documents, notary equipment, and expertise to conduct the closing wherever you prefer — your home, your office, a coffee shop, or any other convenient location.</p>

      <p>Mobile closings have become increasingly popular in recent years, especially since the pandemic accelerated the demand for flexible, convenient services. At <a href="/services/mobile-closings/">OnRecord Title</a>, mobile closings are one of our most requested services.</p>

      <h2>What Is an Office Closing?</h2>

      <p>An office closing is the traditional approach: you go to the title company's physical office (or sometimes a real estate attorney's office) to sign your closing documents. All parties — buyer, seller, agents — may be present, or closings may be conducted separately.</p>

      <p>Our office is conveniently located at <strong>1275 E Fort Union Boulevard, Suite 210, Midvale, Utah</strong> with easy parking and a comfortable signing room.</p>

